 042:         # Before this implementation, AsyncResult and Semaphore
 043:         # maintained the order of notifications, but Event did not.
 044: 
 045:         # In gevent 1.3, before Semaphore extended this class, that
 046:         # was changed to not maintain the order. It was done because
 047:         # Event guaranteed to only call callbacks once (a set) but
 048:         # AsyncResult had no such guarantees. When Semaphore was
 049:         # changed to extend this class, it lost its ordering
 050:         # guarantees. Unfortunately, that made it unfair. There are
 051:         # rare cases that this can starve a greenlet
 052:         # (https://github.com/gevent/gevent/issues/1487) and maybe
 053:         # even lead to deadlock (not tested).
 054: 
 055:         # So in gevent 1.5 we go back to maintaining order. But it's
 056:         # still important not to make duplicate calls, and it's also
 057:         # important to avoid O(n^2) behaviour that can result from
 058:         # naive use of a simple list due to the need to handle removed
 059:         # links in the _notify_links loop. Cython has special support for
 060:         # built-in sets, lists, and dicts, but not ordereddict. Rather than
 061:         # use two data structures, or a dict({link: order}), we simply use a

 063:         # have duplicates called. This makes `unlink` O(n), but we can avoid
